In this study, N-doped porous carbon (denoted as N-doped-MOF-C) was prepared by one-step carbonization of metal organic framework material, NH2-MIL-125. Pd and Ag nanoparticles were immobilized on the N-doped-MOF-C through co-reduction method with NaBH4 as reductant. The results indicated that Pd9Ag1-N-doped-MOF-C catalyst exhibited excellent catalytic activity and selectivity for the catalytic transfer hydrogenation of nitroarenes using formic acid as the renewable hydrogen donor. The high catalytic activity of the catalyst can be attributed to the synergetic interaction between the support and the highly dispersed Pd and Ag metal nanoparticles. Graphical abstract Image 25 Keywords NH2-MIL-125 N-doped porous carbon Nitro-compounds Formic acid Catalytic transfer hydrogenation 1 Introduction Anilines and related derivatives, especially with the functionalized groups, are known as ubiquitous building blocks in the manufacture of dyes, pharmaceuticals, food additives and pigments [1–3]. These compounds are usually prepared by the reduction of corresponding nitro-compounds through a non-catalytic or a catalytic process [4,5]. The non-catalytic reduction is generally performed in the presence of an iron–acid pair, which can result in serious pollution problems and is not an environmentally benign process. In this context, developing novel catalysts with high catalytic performance for catalytic reduction of nitro-compounds is in general preferred and has received considerable attention [6–8]. Catalytic reduction with H2 obviously represents an attractive, more atom-economic alternative. However, the reduction of nitro-compounds with H2 is usually conducted at high pressure and temperature, which suggested that the process is of high-energy consumption. Moreover, H2 is flammable, potentially dangerous and requires special equipment for production, transportation and storage [9]. Alternatively, nitro-compounds can be reduced to aromatic amines by transfer hydrogenation with hydrogen-donor molecules, in which hydrogen is replaced by a hydrogen donor such as formic acid (FA), sodium borohydride, ammonia borane and hydrazine [10]. Among the available hydrogen donors, formic acid has been widely considered as an abundant and promising hydrogen-donor owing to its advantages such as non-toxicity, high stability under ambient conditions, high energy density with a gravimetric hydrogen content of 4.4wt% and the potential to be regenerated by hydrogenation of carbon dioxide (CO2) [11]. Moreover, FA is one of the major by-products in biomass processing. Catalytic transfer hydrogenation using FA as hydrogen source has received an increasing interest in recent years. For example, nitrogen-doped graphene supported iron oxide nanoparticles have been used for transfer hydrogenation of halogenated nitroarenes at 120°C with FA as hydrogen source [12]. Chen and his co-workers [13] fabricated a Pd/g-C3N4-PC catalyst to catalyze transfer hydrogenation of nitroarenes. Yuet al. [9] reported an efficient and versatile gold catalyst for catalyzing reductive transformation of nitro-compounds under a mild condition in the presence of FA. Despite recent progress in this area, the development of efficient and selective catalysts with excellent activity for both dehydrogenation of FA and hydrogenation of nitroarenes continues to be a major challenge and noteworthy task. In general, the synergetic interaction between the metal and support, the type of the support, and the dispersity of the metal nanoparticles play a crucial role for the catalytic performance of the nanocatalysts [14–16]. Until now, various kinds of materials have been explored as the heterogeneous catalyst supports. Porous carbon, especially N-decorated porous carbon, has recently emerged as a kind of most popular functional material with wide applications [17–19]. The introduction of nitrogen atoms in the carbon nano-materials may cause electron modulation to tune their optoelectronic properties and/or chemical activities, and thus further enhance their catalytic performance [20,21]. Therefore, N-decorated porous carbons have been considered as a promising catalyst support for heterogeneous catalysis. However, traditional doping methods often suffer from the problems of non-uniformity distribution of the nitrogen in the material. In situ doping not only is a simple and efficient route but also can incorporate nitrogen atoms into the material homogeneously, which has made it preferred for preparing N-doped porous carbon [22]. On this account, several metal organic frameworks (MOFs) have been served as promising precursors for yielding N-doped porous carbons. The N-doped-MOF-derived porous carbons (N-doped-MOF-C) present large pore volume, high specific surface area, good thermal stability and excellent electrochemical performance, so they have found extensive applications, such as electrocatalysis [23], supercapacitors [24], adsorption [25] and catalysis [26,27]. NH2-MIL-125, Ti8O8(OH)4(bdc-NH2)6 (bdc-NH2: 2-amino-1,4-benzenedicarboxylic acid), is a amine-functionalized metal-organic framework material [28,29]. NH2-MIL-125 is rich in carbon and nitrogen, so it is an ideal precursor to prepare N-doped MOF-C. NH2-MIL-125-derived MOF-C has been applied in photodegradation of methylene blue (MB) [30], as superior anode material for lithium ion batteries [31] and hydrogen storage materials [32]. Herein, we prepared N-doped MOF-C by direct carbonization of NH2-MIL-125. Then AgPd bimetallic nanoparticles were successfully immobilized on N-doped MOF-C by a facilely co-reduction process. Surprisingly, the obtained catalyst exhibited excellent catalytic performance and selectivity for the reduction of nitro compounds with FA as hydrogen source. The turnover frequency (TOF) of the catalyst for the given reaction is higher than that of most of the reported heterogeneous catalysts. 2 Experiment 2.1 Synthesis of N-doped MOF-C N,N-dimethylformamide (DMF) was contacted with 4Ǻ molecular sieve for two days to remove the water. Typically, 2-amino-1,4-benzenedicarboxylic acid (H2BDC-NH2) (2.2g, 12mmol) was dispersed into a mixture of DMF (54mL) and methanol (6mL), and then tetrabutyl titanate (2.4mL, 7mmol) was added into the above solution. After ultrasonic for 10min, the mixture was transferred into a Teflon-lined stainless-steel autoclave, and heated at 150°C for 48h. After centrifugation, the obtained NH2-MIL-125 was washed with DMF and methanol, respectively. Finally, the sample was calcined at 1000°C for 2h under N2 flow and the product was named as N-doped-MOF-C. Ti-free-N-doped-MOF-C was prepared by washing N-doped-MOF-C with HF aqueous. Undoped-MOF-C was fabricated by the same procedure except that H2BDC-NH2 was replaced by H2BDC. 2.2 Synthesis of PdAg-N-doped-MOF-C For the preparation of Pd9Ag1-N-doped-MOF-C, 92mg of N-doped-MOF-C was dispersed in 5mL deionized water. Then a mixture solution of AgNO3 (0.0075mmol) and H2PdCl4 (0.0675mmol) were added into the above solution. The mixture was stirred for 12h at room temperature. The resulting mixture was reduced by fresh NaBH4 aqueous solution (1.5mmol). After centrifugation, the solid catalyst was washed with deionized water, and dried in vacuum at 60°C overnight. The Pd-N-doped-MOF-C, Pd7Ag3-N-doped-MOF-C, Pd5Ag5-N-doped-MOF-C, Pd3Ag7-N-doped-MOF-C, Pd1Ag9-N-doped-MOF-C, Ag-N-doped-MOF-C catalysts were synthesized with the above procedure except that the theoretical molar ratios of Pd and Ag were 10:0, 7:3, 5:5, 3:7, 1:9, 0:10, respectively. The Pd9Ag1-VXC-72, Pd9Ag1-Ti-free-N-doped-MOF-C, Pd9Ag1-undoped-MOF-C catalysts were fabricated by the above procedure except that VXC-72, Ti-free-N-doped-MOF-C and undoped-MOF-C were used as the supports. The contents of Ag and Pd in the composite were determined by ICP-AES. 2.3 Catalytic reduction of nitro-compound A mixture of nitro compound (1mmol), FA (4mmol), potassium formate (PF) (12mmol), catalyst (0.5mol%) and solvent (4mL, EtOH:H2O=1:1) was added into a 25mL round bottom flask. The mixture was stirred at 30°C for an appropriate time depending on the nature of the substrate (as shown in Table 2). Upon completion of the reaction (monitored by TLC), the products were extracted by dichloromethane and determined by GC-MS spectrometer. 3 Results and discussion The morphologies and sizes of Pd-Ag nanoparticles were observed by TEM. As shown in Fig. 1a, the Pd and Ag nanoparticles were homogenously dispersed over the N-doped-MOF-C with a narrow particle size of about 2–5nm. A representative high-resolution TEM image (Fig. 1b) showed that the lattice spacing of PdAg is 0.23nm, which is between the (111) lattice spacing of face-centered cubic (fcc) Pd (0.22nm) and fcc Ag (0.24nm). As shown in the XRD image of Pd9Ag1-N-doped-MOF-C (Fig. S1), neither obvious characteristic peak of Pd (111) at 40.1° nor peak at 38.1° can be observed, which can be ascribed to the low Pd loading used and the well dispersion of AgPd nanoparticles on N-doped-MOF-C. The observation is very similar to the results reported by Zhou [34]. To further confirm the existence of the Ag and Pd nanoparticles, EDX analysis was performed and results are shown in Fig. S2. Obviously, C, N, O, Ti, Ag and Pd existed in the sample. The XPS analysis further confirmed the presence of C, O, N, Ti, Ag and Pd in the catalyst (Fig. S3). The characteristic peaks at 335.3 and 340.6eV (Fig. S4) were attributed to Pd 3d5/2 and Pd 3d3/2, respectively, indicating that the Pd species in the sample Pd9Ag1-N-doped-MOF-C was present in the metallic state. However, the presence of PdO species in the sample was confirmed by the peaks at 337.5 and 342.8eV, which were probably due to the oxidation in an oxygen-containing environment of metallic Pd. The 3d5/2 and 3d3/2 peaks of Ag appeared at 373.5 and 367.8eV (Fig. S4), suggesting that the Ag species in the Pd9Ag1-N-doped-MOF-C was in the metallic state [33]. N2 adsorption–desorption isotherms of N-doped-MOF-C and Pd9Ag1-N-doped-MOF-C were tested at 77K, and the results are shown in Fig. S5. The BET surface areas of N-doped-MOF-C and Pd9Ag1-N-doped-MOF-C were 895.9 and 497.6m2/g, respectively. Based on the Barrett–Joyner–Halenda (BJH) model, the total pore volume of N-doped-MOF-C and Pd9Ag1-N-doped-MOF-C was 0.56cm3 g−1 and 0.42cm3 g−1, respectively. Compared with N-doped-MOF-C, the decrease in BET surface areas and pore volumes of Pd9Ag1-N-doped-MOF-C indicated that the surface areas and the pores of N-doped-MOF-C were partly occupied by Pd and Ag nanoparticles. To examine the activities of different catalysts, the effect of reaction temperature, solvent, dosage of catalyst and the ratio of FA to PF have been carried out using the reduction of p-nitrophenol as a model reaction. As shown in Fig. S6, the catalytic activities of PdxAgy-N-doped-MOF-C were strongly dependent on the ratio of Pd to Ag. As demonstrated in the literature [35], when Ag doped with Pd, the d-band center of Pd shifts with changing the Ag/Pd ratio. When the d-band center of Pd shifts to a suitable value, the catalyst will have the highest dehydrogenation activity from FA. Among the tested catalysts, Pd9Ag1-N-doped-MOF-C exhibited the highest catalytic activity. The product obtained had a high yield of 99% at 30°C after 0.5h. Moreover, the catalytic performance of Pd9Ag1-VXC-72 and Pd9Ag1-Ti-free-N-doped-MOF-C were much lower than that of Pd9Ag1-N-doped-MOF-C. Generally, the charge distribution of carbon atoms can be affected by the neighboring nitrogen dopants, which may create increased defects and more active sites [36]. Moreover, the presence of doped nitrogen heteroatoms on carbon support can stabilize the deposited metal with good dispersion and increase the metal–carbon binding energy [36], which may improves the catalytic activity and stability of the heterogeneous catalyst. For comparison, Pd9Ag1 on undoped-MOF-C support was prepared and its catalytic activity was investigated. The hydrogenation of p-nitrophenol catalyzed by Pd9Ag1-undoped-MOF-C can be completed after 60min, which is much longer than that of Pd9Ag1-N-doped-MOF-C. The above results demonstrated that both the noble metal and the nature of the support play a crucial role in the performance of the catalyst. As shown in Table 1 , no product was obtained in the absence of catalyst (Table 1, entry 1) or with the MOF-C support alone as the catalyst (Table 1, entry 2), which indicates that the catalytic active center is Pd and Ag nanoparticles. Pd9Ag1-N-doped-MOF-C exhibited excellent catalytic activity for the catalytic transfer hydrogenation of nitrophenol (Table 1, entries 3–6). The reactions can be completed after 30, 25, 10, and 5min at 30°C, 40°C, 50°C, and 60°C, respectively. From the data listed in Table 1, it can also be seen that 0.5mol% of Pd9Ag1 was sufficient to achieve complete conversion of nitrophenol in 30min (Table 1, entries 6–9). The effect of type of solvent, such as MeOH, EtOH, H2O and EtOH-H2O, was also investigated. Using MeOH, EtOH and EtOH-H2O (1:1, v/v) as the solvent, the desired product was obtained in 99% yield after 30–40min (Table 1, entries 6, 10–11). However, a longer reaction time (90min) was needed to complete the reaction with H2O as the solvent (Table 1, entry 12), which might due to the low solubility of nitro-compounds in H2O. In order to check if part of hydrogen was originated from ethanol, the hydrogenation of nitrophenol was carried out in the absence of formic acid and potassium formate. No product was obtained after the reaction was conducted for 1h, which indicated that ethanol was not a hydrogen donor in the present catalytic system. Formate can enhance the dehydrogenation of formic acid [37], which is beneficial to the catalytic transfer hydrogenation of the given nitro compound. The effect of molar ratio of FA to PF on the catalytic activity was also investigated by varying the molar ratio of FA to PF from 1:0 to 1:4 (Table 1, entries 6, 13–16). When the molar ratio of FA to PF increased from 1:0 to 1:3, the reaction time decreased from 720min to 30min. With the optimizing conditions in hand, the catalytic activity of Pd9Ag1-N-doped-MOF-C for the reduction of a series of aromatic nitro compounds was investigated. As shown in Table 2 , all aromatic nitro compounds were converted to corresponding amines with excellent yields and selectivity. Both p-nitrophenol and o-nitrophenol were converted rapidly and completely, revealing that a slight space steric hindrance to the hydrogenation of nitro group can be well tolerated (Table 1, entries 1–2). Furthermore, the nitro compounds involving electron-rich (for example, p-methyl, o-methyl, amino, and methoxy groups, Table 2, entries 4–6) and electron-poor groups (halogen atom, cyano groups, Table 2, entries 8–11) were converted to the corresponding amines in good yields at mild conditions. Particularly, the nitroarenes functionalized with the most challenging reducible functional moieties, such as ketone and nitrile groups, were successfully transformed into corresponding amines products with an excellent selectivity (Table 2, entries 7, 11). Moreover, the reduction was also progressed on bulkier molecule, such as 1-nitronaphthalene (Table 2, entry 12). In order to evaluate the catalytic activity of the Pd9Ag1-N-doped-MOF-C catalyst, this was compared with that of other reported catalysts, in terms of hydrogen resource, solvent, reaction temperature, reaction time, and reaction TOF. As shown in Table S1, the Pd9Ag1-N-doped-MOF-C catalyst can efficiently catalyze the reduction of nitro-compound at mild conditions. The TOF of the catalyst is higher than that of most of the reported heterogeneous catalysts. The recycling and reusability of the Pd9Ag1-N-doped-MOF-C catalyst was investigated and results are shown in Supporting information. 4 Conclusion In summary, Pd and Ag nanoparticles are supported on N-doped-MOF-C, which was fabricated by one step carbonization of NH2-MIL-125. The as-prepared Pd9Ag1-N-doped-MOF-C exhibited high catalytic activity towards the catalytic transfer hydrogenation of nitro-compounds with FA as hydrogen source. The use of N-doped-MOF-C as catalyst supports might bring new opportunities in the development of efficient heterogeneous catalyst.
